I get this question all the time! A lot of people think that fine line tattoos are not a real tattoo, and well that can be true if the artist is not tattooing into the correct layer of the skin. With fine line tattoos the end goal is to keep a fine line tattoo right? So as you get your first fine line tattoo and it heals, it is very normal for lines to break fade and maybe disappear. Most artists, at least I hope every artist offers a free touch up with their service, knowing how fineline tattoos heal should recommend you get a touchup. Give-and-take sometimes they heal perfectly and they do not need a touchup, but with that being said overtime with environmental, sun exposure, and product fine line tattoos may fade a little bit more than a traditional. To answer your question, to keep a fine line dainty forever on the body you may need a more frequent touchup than you would a traditional tattoo. I would typically say clients would or could come back for a touch up on their fine line tattoo 5 to 10 years later after they initially got the tattoo. Give and take everyone’s skin type and retention is 100% different. I hope this helps answer this question!

Some of these questions get me into my geeky aesthetician brain! This is a question that a lot of you really don't ask but I need to tell you that it is an important one! Different skin tones are very important to understand as a piercer. Have you heard of the Fitzpatrick scale? If not let me educate you. The Fitzpatrick scale is for skin types. It’s a widely used method of identifying the amount of pigment in a person's skin and tolerance to sun exposure and trauma. When we are piercing, it’s creating trauma to the skin, so understanding how and why skin reacts in different skin tones is so important. If you don't know your Fitzpatrick skin type, swipe to see what yours is and comment below!

Of course not! You are never to old to get a tattoo! BUT with that being said let me explain why a fine line tattoo might not be ideal for maturing skin. As we age our elasticity and collagen fibers break down, causing the skin to have more lag. When getting a fine line tattoo over maturing skin, your lines are not going to heal very straight and may look very distorted. Because fine line is so delicate it is already so difficult as a artist to get those lines crispy and straight. When you are dealing with skin that you cannot control (lack of elasticity and collagen), it is nearly impossible to make a fine line tattoo look good on maturing skin. As an artist, I think it is VERY important to understand these types of issues you could run into. So how can you get a fine line tattoo on maturing skin? Gauging your tattoo needles to a more larger size needle will help make those lines look more steady and clean, not running into the issue of seeing so much error and distorting of the skin/image. Maybe even looking into getting a more traditional style would be your best bet too! 🤍

A tragus piercing sits on the small area of cartilage that partially covers your ear canal. In terms of anatomy, the outer ear is made up of cartilage and skin. They are so cute and can be known to help with migraines, although sometimes cannot be done on every person. It's important to know as a client or a piercer that if the tragus is too small its not worth trying. You are at a high risk of the body rejecting the piercing causing tearing the skin.

I hate to break it to you but we have been lied to our whole lives! Back in the day when you got your ears pierced you were always told "twist your jewelry throughout the day to help it heal". This is such a outdated statement and honestly thinking about it now as an adult I ask… WHY? Lol, did people think your metal stud would just form and attach to your skin? it’s a funny statement to be talking about now. But to answer your questions the answer is NO! Do not twist your freshly pierced jewelry. The more friction you add to your fresh piercing will only irritate the skin more and take twice as long to heal. Also, touching it with dirty hands is putting you at a higher risk of irritation and infection. So what do you do? Just leave it alone. Clean it as directed and leave them alone!

A minimum of 2 weeks! Now this can vary from person to person and their healing process. There are a few reasons you want to stay out of unhygienic waters (pools, hot tubs, lakes) with a fresh tattoo. Reason number one is very straight forward…. bacteria and infection. When getting a tattoo you are creating a open wound. You want to keep that open wound as clean as possible until healed. Number two….you don't know how chemicals or bacteria in the waters will effect the appearance of a tattoo. So how do you know when you are in the clear? Once your skin has healed over the ink (those new layers of the epidermis), your tattoo is completely protected from any open exposure. Now even though your tattoo has new skin over it, you are still in the healing phase for a total of 6 weeks.

EDUCATIONAL POST - the photo on the left is NOT my work. The photo on the right is what I fixed with the help of @the.utah.esthetician at @luxxmedicalspa. I’m making this post educational to let artists know that mistakes can happen as much as all of us didn’t make them. I’m not sure on the details but what was printed out to be tattooed and what was acutally tattooed on the skin was different. The tattoo itself is beautiful, but there was a word that did not make it on the skin. This is why as an artist it is SO important to have your client read word for word, letter by letter ONCE the stencil is placed on the skin. BEFORE you even put your needle into skin you will have the client triple check (this goes for numbers too). This client went to @luxxmedicalspa and had some laser removal done by Addie. We decided to remove a word and add a comma with the correct word to make it make sense. After all of her sessions were done and healed I was able to tattoo it on her. This is a reminder to ALWAYS double and triple check!

A very common question! A piercing bump is a small lump that can appear after a piercing. Piercing bumps occur when the body’s immune system responds to the wound and initiates the healing response. To pinpoint and say exactly how a piercing bump occurs is unknown. Essentially you were creating a wound to the body. This could be hygiene, aftercare, poor quality jewelry, or it’s just your body’s immune system!

There are several reasons why a hollow needle piercing is generally considered better than a piercing gun:

Precision: Hollow needle piercings are performed by professional piercers who have more control over the placement and angle of the piercing. They can accurately position the needle to ensure proper alignment and reduce the risk of complications.

Tissue Damage: Piercing guns use a spring-loaded mechanism to force the jewelry through the skin. This can cause more trauma to the tissue, leading to increased pain, swelling, and potential damage. Hollow needle piercings, on the other hand, create a clean incision, minimizing tissue trauma.

Sterility: Hollow needles used by professional piercers are typically single-use, sterile, and individually packaged. This reduces the risk of infection and ensures a safer piercing experience. Piercing guns, on the other hand, are difficult to sterilize completely, increasing the risk of cross-contamination.

Jewelry Options: Piercing guns often use pre-loaded jewelry that may not be suitable for everyone. Hollow needle piercings allow for a wider range of jewelry options, including high-quality materials like titanium or surgical steel, which are less likely to cause allergic reactions or complications.

 Healing Process: Hollow needle piercings tend to heal better and faster due to the cleaner incision and reduced tissue trauma. The healing time can vary depending on the individual and the specific piercing, but professional piercers can provide appropriate aftercare instructions to promote proper healing.

It's important to note that regulations and practices may vary in different regions, so it's crucial to seek out a reputable and experienced professional piercer who follows proper hygiene and safety protocols. They can provide personalized advice and ensure a safer and more successful piercing experience.

A common question I get about piercings is if you can go swimming or hut tubbing after your get a new piercing! 

Absolutely NOT!! You will want to stay out of any unhygienic waters for at least 2 weeks. Hot tubs, swimming pools, and lakes are unhygienic, dirty, and could possibly have bacteria. This is the number one leading cause to infection to a fresh piercing!
